(Issue:)221 668 MS
(CD2-23-005  Library containers lack exception policy)521 668 MS
[38 0 0 -38 0 0]/_Times-Roman MF
(Section:)221 712 MS
(23 [)521 712 MS
(lib.containers])581 712 MS
(Status:)221 757 MS
(Open \(US\))521 757 MS
(Description:)221 802 MS
(As part of the interface to the standard container templates, users supply classes with member functions that)521 847 MS
(are called during operation of the containers.  These include particularly default and copy construction,)521 892 MS
(assignment, and destruction.  Iterator arguments provide arithmetic and dereference operations.)521 937 MS
(Comparison arguments provide operator\(\).)521 982 MS
(Any of these operations may, in general, result in an exception that propagates out of a container member.)521 1072 MS
(If, when this occurs, the container is left in an inconsistent state, it may be unable to satisfy its requirements)521 1117 MS
(on subsequent operations \(including destruction\), which will cause the program to display undefined)521 1162 MS
(behavior \(crash, if you're lucky; give wrong answers, if not\).)521 1207 MS
(Requiring, for defined behavior, that these operations never throw exceptions is entirely impractical.  At)521 1297 MS
(least, this would forbid placing most standard library objects in a container, because they are allowed to)521 1342 MS
(throw exceptions at unspecified times.  More to the point, exceptions are a response to unexpected events,)521 1387 MS
(and to try to eliminate exceptions is to pretend to eliminate unexpected events. We have exceptions in the)521 1432 MS
(language because unexpected events cannot in general be eliminated.)521 1477 MS
(Requiring that the standard containers satisfy their requirements regardless of exceptions appears to be)521 1567 MS
(equally impractical.  It would impose prohibitive performance and storage overhead on the containers with)521 1612 MS
(only occasional benefit, when recovering from errors.)521 1657 MS
(As it stands, the Standard Library containers are not compatible with exceptions: a program that uses both)521 1747 MS
(\(intentionally or not\) is undefined, and likely to crash. We should not deliver the Draft in this condition.)521 1792 MS
(A resolution for this issue might identify)521 1882 MS
(1. which container operations are subject to disruption, and what operations remain defined after such)521 1972 MS
(disruption;)521 2017 MS
(2. when template argument operations can throw without causing undefined behavior;)521 2062 MS
(This resolution might impose restrictions such as leaving the effect undefined if a container element)521 2152 MS
(destructor throws; and it might impose performance overheads such as requiring that a vector resize)521 2197 MS
(operation be implemented such that it \(temporarily\) requires storage for two copies of each element.)521 2242 MS
(Proposed Resolution:)221 2287 MS
