(In case the insertion is into a char stream, widen\(c \) will usually be c.)669 441 MS
(I conclude that widen is always applied once a char is inserted into any kind of output stream \(be it a stream)521 531 MS
(for char, wchar_t, or a generic charT\). On the other hand widen is never applied if a wchar_t or a generic)521 576 MS
(charT is inserted. Why is this asymmetry? What is the purpose of widening a char even if is inserted into a)521 621 MS
(char stream?)521 666 MS
(Discussion:)221 711 MS
(The purpose of widening a char even if is inserted into a char stream could be to allow for character)521 756 MS
(encodings inside a stream that are different from the compiler\222s native encoding. If this were the intent then)521 801 MS
(all )521 846 MS
(inserters and  extractors and all the unformatted operations would have to apply narrowing and)570 846 MS
(widening. The draft does not require this, only in the case of the char inserter for char output streams.)521 891 MS
(I think a clarification is needed that says whether the encoding used inside the stream always has to be)521 981 MS
(compiler's native encoding or not. If encodings different from the native encoding are allowed then it needs)521 1026 MS
(to be specified which operations apply widen/narrow. This would be a major change, and I doubt that there)521 1071 MS
(is a need for non-native character encodings inside a stream.)521 1116 MS
